\par 20. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10355627 MINORS AND THE ESSENTIAL WORK ORDER }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 
\par 
\par There appears to have been little further comment on the passing of the amendment to the Essential Work 
(Coalmining Industry) Order. Opinions differ as to the reasons for this and range from the view that it has been quietly accepted as a necessary war measure, to the suggestion that the miner knows his present value to the country and feels reasonably sure
 that the Government will not risk enforcing the amendment. Mental slowness and lack of interest are also thought to be possible causes, although the belief is held that the seriousness of the present position is being more fully appreciated by miners.

\par 
\par Among managements and miners' 'representatives the amendment seems to have been welcomed - among the former because it is believed to meet- the need for dealing swiftly and efficaciously...with offenders in the pits, and among the latter because both they
 and the miners are glad that the question of dealing with absentees has been taken out of their hands. It is suggested that when a prosecution takes place it must be "a good case of a genuine slacker". A case of this kind, it is believed, will not arouse
 the sympathy of the miners and will discourage absenteeism.
\par 
\par The belief that-the only real solution of the coal problem is to release miners from the army is reported by two Regions to be current. Nationalization is also suggested as the solution of the industry's troubles.
\par 
\par Surprise that it should be found necessary further to restrict the miner's liberty has been mentioned, and impatience with "trifling amendments" compared with the "hideous struggle at Stalingrad" has been expressed.
\par 
\par Among the larger pits there is reported to be satisfaction that transfer to other 'scheduled undertakings is to be prevented.
\par 
\par The new order, it is suggested, may have been the cause of a reported increase in production last week in some pits in the Durham area.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10355627 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 (1.8.10.11.12.)
\par 
\par 21. U}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10355627 .S. TROOPS IN GREAT BRITAIN }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 
\par 
\par Comment on this subject has declined considerably, but it is on the whole favourable. The coloured troops are referred to as "a fine lot of men". The attitude of the white U.S. troops towards them still arouses interest. Two Regions report continued co
mment on the high pay of U.S. troops, and there is again mention of "careless talk" and fast driving.
\par 
\par Allegations that U.S. troops are being overcharged in shops and public houses are again made (one Region), and there is an isolated case reported of an American making a similar complaint.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10355627 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 (3.4.5.6.7.8.11.12.21 Cambridge, Manchester, Bristol, Glasgow P.C.s.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10355627 22. FOOD}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 
\par 
\par Satisfaction with the food situation continues to be reported. Lord Woolton's warning about stricter rationing is said to have been taken well in two Regions; but has "caused perturbation" in the North Eastern Region.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7360258 Unfavourable}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180  comments reported on certain aspects}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10355627  of the food situation include:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9786180 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10355627 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid10355627 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 (a) The shortage of shell eggs.(Four Regions and Postal Censorship).
\par 
\par (b) The increase in the price of bread. The farthings in the price are said to be leading to the purchase of two loaves when only one is needed, with consequent waste. (Four Regions)
\par 
\par (c) The small allowance of sugar for jam, making. (Three Regions 
and Postal. Censorship) Housewives in the North Midland Region are said to be complaining that their jam made in May and June is going bad. The opinion is expressed that this may be happening because the sugar is beet, and not cane.
\par 
\par (d) The high price and unequal distribution of fruit. (Three Regions)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10030560 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 
\par (e) The cheese ration is too big. The lack of variety is also commented on. (Two Regions)
\par 
\par (f) The shortage of fish. From the North Western Region, the conviction is reported among those in the industry that the fish zoning scheme will fail. (Two Regions) 
\par 
\par (g) The shortage of vinegar. (Two Regions)
\par 
\par (h) The habit of sieving national flour is said to be increasing. (Two Regions)
\par 
\par (i) The purchase of large quantities of oatmeal "for uses other than human 'Consumption".}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10030560  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 (One Region)
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid9786180 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 
The public are reported to be interested in the Ministry of Food advertisements and instructions. The widespread publicity in favour of potatoes is generally understood, although not always accepted. In Wales it is said to create suspicion; "Last year 
it was carrots for health, sight, etc., and we were told we could not expect to live unless we ate carrots. Now the same tale about potatoes".
\par (1.2.3.4.5.6.7.8.10.12.21 Cambridge, Edinburgh, Reading, Aberdeen, Carlisle, Manchester, Cardiff.P.0 s.32)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7360258 23. CLOTHING}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 
\par 
\par The "poor quality" and "shoddiness" of some utility clothing "as compared with the attractiveness and good quality of other utility garments" is rep}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7360258 orted to be causing dissatisfac}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 tion. Utility stockings are especially mentioned in this connection. They are said to be shapeless and absolutely lacking in reasonable durability. The popular view is that they are just a waste of coupons".
\par 
\par The shortage of warm underclothing in large sizes for men and women is reported from Wales. From the North Midland Region comes the complaint that O.S. clothing is not being produced by manufacturers.
\par 
\par The fitting out of children for their first year at a Secondary School and the maintenance of the uniform are said to cause hardship especially in regard to coupons. The general opinion in Wales is "that school uniforms should be optional".
\par 
\par "The long delays experienced in getting repairs to boots and shoes executed are reported to cause hardship, especially to poorer people who may only possess one or two pairs".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7360258 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 (1.3.5.7.8.32)
\par 
\par 24. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7360258 CIVIL DEFENCE UNIFORMS}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 
\par 
\par The provision of new uniforms for Civil Defence workers is reported from three Regions to be regarded as "a complete waste of money", not only by the public but by wardens themselves.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7360258  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 
Some of the latter point out that "much valuable time would be lost in turning out at an alert if they stopped to don the uniform", and that "in practice the uniform would only be used for parades". Displeasure at the idea is also reported from the Army 
and the Home Guard: "Mere is misunderstanding about rank markings".}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7360258 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 (1.5.6.10.32)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7360258 25. CARELESS TALK}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 
\par 
\par Careless talk, which is said to have greatly increased in the Southern Region, is reported from three Regions this week; "particularly amongst
 Service personnel, who seem only too ready to disclose their station and the type of work they are engaged upon".}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10030560  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 
It is suggested that "a fresh campaign against careless talk might prove useful".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7360258 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 (3.5.6)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7360258 26. RUMOURS}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180 
\par 
\par The Ark Royal story continues. She is said to be nearly fit to put to sea again. Naval ratings are alleged to have started this rumour in the London area.
\par 
\par Irish labourer who leave the country after 6, months to avoid income tax are thought to be a particularly dangerous source of information for the enemy. They are said to queue up outside the German Embassy in Dublin to lay information at \'a32 a time. It
 is rumoured that an enemy passenger plane flies over Watford nightly on its way to Dublin, unmolested.
\par 
\par Second front rumours continue. Portugal is now named as a place for attack. Points on the South Coast which are to be evacuated are discussed. Pipe-lines running down to the sea at certain points are thought to be for oil for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7360258 refuelling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9786180  when the second front comes.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10030560 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10030560 
